04269nam a22006255i 9780292792975DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927929757 a10.7560/7219442doi  a(DE-B1597)587547  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN2287.K7bH67 2010eb 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a791.4502/80922221 aHorton, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aErnie Kovacs & Early TV Comedy :bNothing in Moderation /cAndrew Horton. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Nothing in Moderation -- t1 } An Overview of the Postwar Era and the Ernie Kovacs Shows in the Context of American Television Comedy -- t2 } The Flow of the Philadelphia and New York Kovacs Shows:Comic Surrealism, Verbal and Visual -- t3 } Silents Please! Ernie, California, and Working with Music, Sound, and Surrealistic Visuals on His Specials -- t4 } Ernie in the Movies: From Comic Director to Supporting Character Actor -- t5 } The Kovacs Legacy: “I Don’t Know. I Just Do It!” -- tAppendix: Summary Of Ernie Kovacs’ Personal Life -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the pioneers of television, Ernie Kovacs was one of the most original and imaginative comedians. His zany, irreverent, and surprising humor not only entertained audiences throughout the 1950s and early 1960s, but also inspired a host of later comedies and comedians, including Monty Python, David Letterman, much of Saturday Night Live, Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In, Captain Kangaroo, and even Sesame Street. Kovacs created laughter through wildly creative comic jokes, playful characterizations, hilarious insights, and wacky experiments. "Nothing in moderation," his motto and epitaph, sums up well Kovacs's wholehearted approach to comedy and life. In this book, Andrew Horton offers the first sustained look at Ernie Kovacs's wide-ranging and lasting contributions to the development of TV comedy. He discusses in detail Kovacs's work in New York, which included The Ernie Kovacs Show (CBS prime time 1952–1953), The Ernie Kovacs Show (NBC daytime variety 1956–1957), Tonight (NBC late-night comedy/variety 1956-1957), and a number of quiz shows. Horton also looks at Kovacs's work in Los Angeles and in feature film comedy. He vividly describes how Kovacs and his comic co-conspirators created offbeat characters and zany situations that subverted expectations and upended the status quo. Most of all, Horton demonstrates that Kovacs grasped the possibility for creating a fresh genre of comedy through the new medium of television and exploited it to the fullest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aComedianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aTelevision comedieszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292792975423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292792975/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK